1051
01:08:40,658 --> 01:08:42,242
[CASEY SCREAMS]

1052
01:08:42,325 --> 01:08:43,326
[LAUGHS]

1053
01:08:43,410 --> 01:08:44,744
Move or sink, kid.

1054
01:08:44,828 --> 01:08:46,996
You were actually prepared for that?

1055
01:08:56,673 --> 01:08:58,341
- My hat.
- Leave it.

1056
01:08:58,508 --> 01:09:00,092
No, no, no. I can’t go without it.

1057
01:09:07,015 --> 01:09:08,142
It’s my dad’s.

1058
01:09:09,852 --> 01:09:11,520
Now I get it.

1059
01:09:11,687 --> 01:09:13,814
Too smart for your own good.

1060
01:09:14,857 --> 01:09:18,277
Father never understood you,
never supported you.

1061
01:09:18,485 --> 01:09:23,282
And now you wear his hat
as a badge of rebellion, right?

1062
01:09:24,658 --> 01:09:26,994
No. My dad is amazing.

1063
01:09:28,870 --> 01:09:30,162
[GROANS]

1064
01:09:30,537 --> 01:09:32,706
Oh, wait a second.

1065
01:09:33,790 --> 01:09:36,042
We’re not talking about me, are we?

1066
01:09:38,627 --> 01:09:41,212
Why don’t we just get you
to your amazing dad

1067
01:09:41,379 --> 01:09:42,839
and pretend this never happened?

1068
01:09:43,798 --> 01:09:44,841
Hop on.

1069
01:09:47,802 --> 01:09:49,429
- The battery’s dead.
- No, it’s not.

1070
01:09:49,512 --> 01:09:50,638
Then maybe it’s the points.

1071
01:09:50,722 --> 01:09:51,890
No, it’s not.

1072
01:09:51,973 --> 01:09:53,183
When’s the last time you checked...

1073
01:09:53,266 --> 01:09:55,393
You know, you’re not helping. You...

1074
01:09:57,353 --> 01:09:58,688
Get down. Now.

1075
01:10:13,411 --> 01:10:14,579
Wait.

1076
01:10:17,874 --> 01:10:18,917
Hello, Frank.

1077
01:10:26,674 --> 01:10:28,258
Are you going to shoot me?

1078
01:10:30,302 --> 01:10:31,594
I’m deciding.

1079
01:10:31,677 --> 01:10:33,304
Could you decide in the truck?

1080
01:10:33,387 --> 01:10:35,181
Because we really should get going.

1081
01:10:37,057 --> 01:10:38,265
Wait.

1082
01:10:38,349 --> 01:10:40,558
Why? So more robots can show up?

1083
01:10:43,269 --> 01:10:44,521
She’s one of them.

1084
01:10:44,604 --> 01:10:46,314
Yeah, I know. Are you coming or not?

1085
01:10:52,320 --> 01:10:54,614
Aw... Move over.

1086
01:11:14,175 --> 01:11:16,177
- Frank...
- Not yet.

1087
01:11:17,845 --> 01:11:20,430
What are you thinking?
Why would you drag her into this?

1088
01:11:20,514 --> 01:11:24,226
I didn’t drag her into anything.
I gave her a pin.

1089
01:11:24,309 --> 01:11:26,436
She did the rest.

1090
01:11:26,520 --> 01:11:27,563
Just like you.

1091
01:11:27,646 --> 01:11:31,066
Oh, don’t even.
Where did you even find the pin?

1092
01:11:31,191 --> 01:11:32,693
I was there. They destroyed ‘em.

1093
01:11:32,776 --> 01:11:35,821
Not all of them.
I made it out with nearly a dozen.

1094
01:11:35,904 --> 01:11:37,364
So you give one to a teenager.

1095
01:11:37,447 --> 01:11:40,867
Hey, I got a 73 on the
Feinberg/Dusseldorf scale or whatever.

1096
01:11:40,951 --> 01:11:43,160
- You got a 73? That’s not possible.
- Hmm.

1097
01:11:43,244 --> 01:11:45,496
He’s jealous because he scored a 41.

1098
01:11:45,663 --> 01:11:47,290
You know what? I was eleven.

1099
01:11:47,540 --> 01:11:48,748
I was eleven!

1100
01:11:49,124 --> 01:11:51,084
Hey, don’t touch that!

1101
01:11:51,167 --> 01:11:55,672
This is a one-kiloton detonation.
It is not a toy.

1102
01:11:55,755 --> 01:11:57,966
Do not mess with my stuff.

1103
01:11:58,049 --> 01:11:59,217
- You got it?
- Sorry!

1104
01:11:59,301 --> 01:12:01,803
I didn’t begin with her, you know.

1105
01:12:01,886 --> 01:12:04,723
I wasted years
on other potential candidates.

1106
01:12:04,806 --> 01:12:06,474
Potential candidates? For what?

1107
01:12:07,976 --> 01:12:10,103
[CHUCKLING] That’s beautiful.

1108
01:12:10,186 --> 01:12:12,439
You still think you’re recruiting,
Don’t you?

1109
01:12:12,522 --> 01:12:14,149
Do not ask her any more questions.

1110
01:12:14,232 --> 01:12:16,026
She’s gonna do her
countermeasure shutdown thing.

1111
01:12:16,109 --> 01:12:17,444
What countermeasure shutdown thing?

1112
01:12:17,527 --> 01:12:19,321
Did you tell her you had
a countermeasure shutdown thing?

1113
01:12:19,404 --> 01:12:21,031
She was annoying me.

1114
01:12:21,114 --> 01:12:23,033
[STAMMERING] You lied?

1115
01:12:23,116 --> 01:12:24,451
Ah, get used to that, kid.

1116
01:12:24,534 --> 01:12:26,494
One minute,
she’s promising you a beautiful future,

1117
01:12:26,578 --> 01:12:29,289
the next thing you know,
she’s leading it to your house to kill you.

1118
01:12:29,372 --> 01:12:32,375
I’m sorry, but time is running out
and you needed motivation.

1119
01:12:32,459 --> 01:12:33,543
Motivation for what?

1120
01:12:34,210 --> 01:12:35,837
We need to go back over, Frank.

1121
01:12:35,920 --> 01:12:37,588
Back over there?

1122
01:12:37,671 --> 01:12:39,255
Yes, yes, Frank,
we need to go back over.

1123
01:12:39,339 --> 01:12:40,839
Good. Great. That’s just great.

1124
01:12:40,922 --> 01:12:44,051
You know, hey, I got stung by a bee.
Let’s jump on the hive.

1125
01:12:44,635 --> 01:12:46,135
That’s a terrible analogy.

1126
01:12:46,385 --> 01:12:49,096
That’s a fantastic analogy.
What do you know about analogies?

1127
01:12:49,180 --> 01:12:51,432
You know, you’re impossible to talk to
when you’re like this.

1128
01:12:51,515 --> 01:12:54,935
I am like this
because you derailed my life.

1129
01:12:55,019 --> 01:12:56,062
Again.

1130
01:12:56,145 --> 01:12:58,606
Frank, it’s not personal.

1131
01:12:59,565 --> 01:13:01,233
It’s just programming.

1132
01:13:01,317 --> 01:13:02,318
Ah.

1133
01:13:02,860 --> 01:13:03,903
We’re here!

1134
01:13:11,535 --> 01:13:12,619
FRANK: Where are you going?

1135
01:13:12,702 --> 01:13:15,663
This is where
your wire station’s located, isn’t it?

1136
01:13:15,746 --> 01:13:17,414
We need to get to The Spectacle.

1137
01:13:17,498 --> 01:13:18,540
- Spectacle?
- Hey.

1138
01:13:18,624 --> 01:13:19,832
Are you insane?

1139
01:13:19,916 --> 01:13:21,124
They know that you sent her to me.

1140
01:13:21,208 --> 01:13:22,416
They’re gonna be waiting for us.

1141
01:13:22,500 --> 01:13:25,211
Fine. Give me the Edison tube
and we’ll go without you.

1142
01:13:25,294 --> 01:13:27,296
I don’t have the Edison tube.

1143
01:13:27,380 --> 01:13:29,215
It’s in your bag.

1144
01:13:29,298 --> 01:13:31,008
I have x-ray vision.

1145
01:13:31,092 --> 01:13:32,259
When did you get x-ray vision?

1146
01:13:32,343 --> 01:13:34,011
Oh, she’s full of surprises.

1147
01:13:34,095 --> 01:13:35,387
I know all about her surprises.

1148
01:13:35,470 --> 01:13:38,847
Chief among them is this.
She doesn’t care about you.

1149
01:13:39,431 --> 01:13:43,184
All that charm and the sense of purpose,
and the cute little smile...

1150
01:13:43,351 --> 01:13:44,977
it’s all just software.

1151
01:13:45,061 --> 01:13:47,355
It’s ones and zeroes. That’s it.

1152
01:13:48,606 --> 01:13:51,734
Trust me, when you get there,
you’re on your own.

1153
01:13:52,694 --> 01:13:54,529
What happened to you two?

1154
01:13:54,612 --> 01:13:55,988
He thinks I hurt him.

1155
01:13:56,072 --> 01:13:59,909
No, you hurt a dumb kid
that was stupid enough to fall...

1156
01:14:00,284 --> 01:14:02,120
[GRUMBLES]

1157
01:14:04,789 --> 01:14:06,624
You were many things, Frank Walker.

1158
01:14:09,669 --> 01:14:11,461
But you were never dumb.

1159
01:14:16,967 --> 01:14:18,719
Why don’t you just give me
the Edison tube, and...

1160
01:14:18,802 --> 01:14:20,302
FRANK: I’m not giving you anything.

1161
01:14:20,428 --> 01:14:21,636
I’m...

1162
01:14:26,975 --> 01:14:28,309
All right.

1163
01:14:28,476 --> 01:14:31,187
You want in? I’ll bring you in.

1164
01:14:31,354 --> 01:14:32,605
Why not?

1165
01:14:32,856 --> 01:14:34,774
It’s better than waiting
around here and getting

1166
01:14:34,858 --> 01:14:36,860
hunted and killed, et cetera, et cetera.

1167
01:14:36,943 --> 01:14:38,027
That’s the spirit.

1168
01:14:38,111 --> 01:14:40,572
“Et cetera”? What’s the “et cetera”?

1169
01:14:52,333 --> 01:14:54,293
[MACHINE POWERING UP]

1170
01:15:04,720 --> 01:15:06,220
What kind of cables are these?

1171
01:15:06,304 --> 01:15:07,680
The kind that transmit people.

1172
01:15:08,097 --> 01:15:09,681
People? Like us?

1173
01:15:09,765 --> 01:15:11,308
What, like a miniature teleport...

1174
01:15:11,391 --> 01:15:12,683
Do I have to explain everything?

1175
01:15:13,142 --> 01:15:16,519
Can’t you just be amazed and move on?

1176
01:15:16,603 --> 01:15:19,272
This is all wired to the dish up there.

1177
01:15:22,692 --> 01:15:24,652
Are you... Are you using satellite?

1178
01:15:27,029 --> 01:15:28,363
I know how things work.

1179
01:15:29,364 --> 01:15:31,032
Well, zippity-doo for you.

1180
01:15:32,824 --> 01:15:35,035
Wrap this around your eyes, tight.

1181
01:15:35,202 --> 01:15:36,286
Why?

1182
01:15:36,369 --> 01:15:38,371
Because justice is blind.

1183
01:15:39,455 --> 01:15:41,499
Just do it, kid.

1184
01:15:42,333 --> 01:15:45,294
You want me to put this over my head?

1185
01:15:46,545 --> 01:15:48,088
If this takes off my eyebrows...

1186
01:15:48,172 --> 01:15:50,424
Shut up, open your mouth,
tilt your head back.

1187
01:15:51,050 --> 01:15:52,885
[SPITS] Ugh. What is that?

1188
01:15:53,844 --> 01:15:55,428
It’s powder. Are we at van’t Hoff?

1189
01:15:56,054 --> 01:15:57,514
Good to go!

1190
01:15:57,597 --> 01:15:59,724
FRANK: Good. You set it for the Tower?

1191
01:15:59,891 --> 01:16:01,518
There is still a receiver there?

1192
01:16:01,601 --> 01:16:02,852
ATHENA: Last I checked.

1193
01:16:02,936 --> 01:16:04,103
How long ago was that?

1194
01:16:07,565 --> 01:16:08,817
25 years ago.

1195
01:16:11,110 --> 01:16:12,402
Roughly.

1196
01:16:17,741 --> 01:16:18,784
They threw you out, too?

1197
01:16:20,410 --> 01:16:22,871
CASEY: Okay, guys. Killer robots.

1198
01:16:23,914 --> 01:16:24,998
All right.

1199
01:16:25,082 --> 01:16:27,709
It’s gonna be
bright, cold, and really loud.

1200
01:16:27,793 --> 01:16:31,672
You’re gonna lose 90% of your
blood sugar in 1/100th of a second

1201
01:16:31,755 --> 01:16:33,465
and you’re gonna wish you were dead.

1202
01:16:33,549 --> 01:16:34,716
But then it’ll be over.

1203
01:16:36,176 --> 01:16:37,719
Don’t pee on us.

1204
01:16:37,803 --> 01:16:40,012
This sounds spectacular.

1205
01:16:42,265 --> 01:16:44,350
Why now? Why her?

1206
01:16:45,142 --> 01:16:47,018
Because she hasn’t given up.

1207
01:16:47,185 --> 01:16:48,769
You think she can fix it.

1208
01:16:49,937 --> 01:16:51,772
What makes you say that?

1209
01:16:54,650 --> 01:16:56,526
Can she, Athena?

1210
01:16:56,693 --> 01:16:58,069
I have no idea.

1211
01:16:59,737 --> 01:17:01,489
Let’s go find out.

1212
01:17:15,295 --> 01:17:17,297
[VOICE BREAKING]
Is it... Is this normal?

1213
01:17:22,302 --> 01:17:24,012
[DISTORTED YELLING]

1214
01:17:25,555 --> 01:17:26,847
[DISTORTED GROANING]

1215
01:17:36,230 --> 01:17:37,814
[GASPING]

1216
01:17:37,898 --> 01:17:39,357
Thirsty.

1217
01:17:39,441 --> 01:17:41,650
[MOANING] Dying. I think I’m dying.

1218
01:17:41,734 --> 01:17:43,819
- FRANK: You’re not dying!
- I’m dying.

1219
01:17:43,903 --> 01:17:45,654
There’s Coke in the fridge.

1220
01:17:45,738 --> 01:17:47,156
[GASPING]

1221
01:17:50,034 --> 01:17:52,036
[PANTING]

1222
01:17:56,165 --> 01:17:58,167
[GULPING]

1223
01:18:03,964 --> 01:18:05,507
Help yourself.

1224
01:18:05,841 --> 01:18:08,344
We have no idea how many are here

1225
01:18:08,427 --> 01:18:09,887
but we’re damn sure
they know we’re coming.

1226
01:18:09,970 --> 01:18:11,972
So, we move quickly. You follow me.

1227
01:18:12,181 --> 01:18:14,099
No questions. Got it?

1228
01:18:15,142 --> 01:18:16,310
Got it.

1229
01:18:18,186 --> 01:18:19,854
[BURPING]

1230
01:18:24,859 --> 01:18:25,902
Excuse me.

1231
01:18:48,174 --> 01:18:49,550
We’re in Paris?

1232
01:18:49,634 --> 01:18:51,260
Would you stop being so amazed?

1233
01:18:51,344 --> 01:18:52,552
I thought you wanted me to be amazed.

1234
01:18:52,678 --> 01:18:54,554
I want you to stop yammer...

1235
01:18:55,055 --> 01:18:57,891
[MAN ANNOUNCING OVER PA
IN FRENCH]

1236
01:19:00,227 --> 01:19:01,770
Tower’s closing.

1237
01:19:01,937 --> 01:19:03,521
Aw, hell.

1238
01:19:09,110 --> 01:19:10,277
Come on.

1239
01:19:10,403 --> 01:19:12,530
Now, you and I are gonna be
on a watch list,

1240
01:19:12,613 --> 01:19:15,700
but they may not have your facial
recognition profile uploaded yet.

1241
01:19:15,783 --> 01:19:16,951
- “May not”?
- May not.

1242
01:19:17,034 --> 01:19:20,371
So, you walk over there,
you take this, you tap him on the neck.

1243
01:19:20,454 --> 01:19:21,872
If he’s human, it knocks him right out.

1244
01:19:21,956 --> 01:19:23,582
- And if it’s a robot?
- Uh...

1245
01:19:23,708 --> 01:19:25,459
- [CLANGS]
- Hey!

1246
01:19:25,543 --> 01:19:27,127
You’ll just piss it off.

1247
01:19:27,210 --> 01:19:28,420
Fantastic.

1248
01:19:31,797 --> 01:19:33,924
She’s got guts. You gotta give her that.

1249
01:19:34,091 --> 01:19:36,051
[MAN SPEAKING FRENCH]

1250
01:19:36,135 --> 01:19:38,971
CASEY: Ah, yes,
but I was just, you know...

1251
01:19:39,304 --> 01:19:40,305
[CLANGS]

1252
01:19:41,056 --> 01:19:42,348
Human!

1253
01:19:59,157 --> 01:20:01,366
The French hated this thing
when Eiffel first unveiled it

1254
01:20:01,450 --> 01:20:02,784
at the Paris World’s Fair.

1255
01:20:02,868 --> 01:20:04,368
They thought it was an eyesore.

1256
01:20:04,452 --> 01:20:07,329
Eiffel didn’t care, though.
It wasn’t meant to be a monument.

1257
01:20:07,413 --> 01:20:08,748
It was meant to find another world.

1258
01:20:09,749 --> 01:20:13,252
<i>Les Quatre Premiers.</i>
Plus Ultra’s First Four.

1259
01:20:13,753 --> 01:20:15,171
They were a part of all this?

1260
01:20:15,254 --> 01:20:18,257
Eiffel, Jules Verne, Tesla,

1261
01:20:18,424 --> 01:20:20,259
and Mr. Edison.

1262
01:20:21,969 --> 01:20:23,261
They designed this antenna
that we’re inside.

1263
01:20:23,344 --> 01:20:25,220
Wait, what?
The Eiffel Tower is an antenna?

1264
01:20:25,304 --> 01:20:27,139
Now I finally answer your question,
you’re gonna interrupt me?

1265
01:20:27,556 --> 01:20:28,682
Yes.

1266
01:20:28,849 --> 01:20:32,061
Tesla designed the antenna to observe
every kind of frequency out there.

1267
01:20:32,144 --> 01:20:34,563
Subspace, trans-dimensional,
you name it.

1268
01:20:34,646 --> 01:20:37,316
And they found exactly
what they were looking for.

1269
01:20:37,399 --> 01:20:40,568
And then Edison tried to take credit for it,
because these two hate each other.

1270
01:20:40,651 --> 01:20:42,027
- ATHENA: Frank...
- Because of alternating...

1271
01:20:42,110 --> 01:20:43,402
Stay on topic.

1272
01:20:43,819 --> 01:20:45,237
Yeah. All right, well...

1273
01:20:46,739 --> 01:20:50,700
There were always rumours
of a secret entrance

1274
01:20:50,867 --> 01:20:53,452
the Four kept just for themselves.

1275
01:20:54,703 --> 01:20:57,080
A one-way ticket

1276
01:20:57,246 --> 01:20:59,540
in case of emergencies.

1277
01:21:03,544 --> 01:21:04,670
The Spectacle.

1278
01:21:05,129 --> 01:21:07,340
[PATRIOTIC MUSIC PLAYING]

1279
01:21:31,614 --> 01:21:32,615
[HORN BLOWING]

1280
01:21:37,662 --> 01:21:39,288
You ain’t seen nothing yet, kid.

1281
01:21:40,206 --> 01:21:42,500
[RUMBLING]

1282
01:21:59,851 --> 01:22:01,686
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

1283
01:22:35,094 --> 01:22:37,263
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

1284
01:22:45,104 --> 01:22:46,856
It’s a rocket.

1285
01:22:51,319 --> 01:22:52,695
They’re coming.

1286
01:22:53,613 --> 01:22:54,655
All right.

1287
01:23:12,924 --> 01:23:14,132
Buckle up!

1288
01:23:25,894 --> 01:23:28,063
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

1289
01:23:31,608 --> 01:23:32,651
What’d he say?

1290
01:23:32,734 --> 01:23:34,318
Pretty much what you’d expect.

1291
01:23:34,401 --> 01:23:35,693
Tell him to hang on.

1292
01:23:37,237 --> 01:23:38,821
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

1293
01:23:50,250 --> 01:23:52,168
Whoo-hoo!

1294
01:24:01,511 --> 01:24:03,513
[CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING]

1295
01:24:47,181 --> 01:24:48,391
Why are we going back?

1296
01:24:48,474 --> 01:24:50,685
We’re not. We’re going through

1297
01:24:50,768 --> 01:24:52,103
to another dimension.

1298
01:24:52,186 --> 01:24:55,064
So we blasted into outer space
just to get a running start?

1299
01:24:55,565 --> 01:24:57,525
This part may get a little weird.

1300
01:25:24,844 --> 01:25:25,845
[GRUNTS]

1301
01:25:35,605 --> 01:25:36,606
[GROANS]

1302
01:25:47,825 --> 01:25:49,409
[METAL SCRAPING]

1303
01:25:53,455 --> 01:25:56,040
ATHENA: Casey. Wake up.

1304
01:25:58,376 --> 01:26:00,168
Casey.

1305
01:26:01,252 --> 01:26:03,797
Casey. Wake up.

1306
01:26:03,963 --> 01:26:05,090
We’re here.

1307
01:26:51,969 --> 01:26:53,679
Now what?

1308
01:26:54,346 --> 01:26:55,764
You tell me.

1309
01:26:56,557 --> 01:26:58,559
I tell you? This was your idea.

1310
01:26:58,642 --> 01:26:59,768
I don’t have ideas.

1311
01:27:00,185 --> 01:27:02,104
I just find the people who do.

1312
01:27:02,187 --> 01:27:03,855
- So there’s no plan?
- There’s a plan.

1313
01:27:03,938 --> 01:27:05,690
You just haven’t come up with it yet.

1314
01:27:06,691 --> 01:27:08,776
But you should do that soon.

1315
01:27:12,613 --> 01:27:14,657
Ah, that’s just terrific.

1316
01:27:15,700 --> 01:27:16,992
Here, hide this.

1317
01:27:18,243 --> 01:27:19,661
Absolutely.

1318
01:27:19,744 --> 01:27:21,955
Wait. Is that
the one-kiloton detonation thingy

1319
01:27:22,038 --> 01:27:23,290
you told me not to play with?

1320
01:27:23,373 --> 01:27:24,665
Right now, it’s our insurance policy.

1321
01:27:24,748 --> 01:27:27,168
There’s a good chance they’re gonna try
to kill us right out of the gate.

1322
01:27:27,251 --> 01:27:29,420
So we’re just gonna stand here?

1323
01:27:29,503 --> 01:27:32,214
Well, you wanted to see Tomorrowland.

1324
01:27:33,174 --> 01:27:34,717
Here it comes.

1325
01:28:00,910 --> 01:28:02,410
Take the bag.

1326
01:28:08,082 --> 01:28:09,292
Frank.

1327
01:28:09,375 --> 01:28:10,585
David.

1328
01:28:11,419 --> 01:28:12,921
You look well.

1329
01:28:13,087 --> 01:28:14,422
Age becomes you.

1330
01:28:14,589 --> 01:28:16,216
Thanks. You should try it.

1331
01:28:17,050 --> 01:28:19,969
I don’t know. I think I’ll just keep
drinking my shake every morning.

1332
01:28:20,053 --> 01:28:22,347
- Comes in chocolate now.
- Ah. Yum.

1333
01:28:26,267 --> 01:28:27,559
Hello, Athena.

1334
01:28:27,935 --> 01:28:30,270
I started to think
you were never coming home.

1335
01:28:30,979 --> 01:28:32,647
Where, oh, where have you been?

1336
01:28:32,939 --> 01:28:34,190
Doing my job.

1337
01:28:34,649 --> 01:28:36,233
Your job?

1338
01:28:36,316 --> 01:28:37,567
I’m sorry. Were we not clear

1339
01:28:37,651 --> 01:28:39,819
when we suspended
your recruitment protocols?

1340
01:28:39,945 --> 01:28:42,530
I got that sense when you
called me “bloody obsolete”

1341
01:28:42,613 --> 01:28:44,073
and tried to disassemble me.

1342
01:28:45,573 --> 01:28:48,201
Well, you’ve certainly
caused quite a commotion

1343
01:28:48,284 --> 01:28:51,829
by launching an antique rocket ship
out of the Eiffel Tower.

1344
01:28:53,456 --> 01:28:55,166
Under normal circumstances,

1345
01:28:55,250 --> 01:28:58,627
we’d be working overtime to convince
everyone it was just an elaborate hoax.

1346
01:28:58,710 --> 01:29:01,046
Fortunately, for all of us,

1347
01:29:01,338 --> 01:29:02,838
doesn’t really matter now, does it?

1348
01:29:03,297 --> 01:29:05,091
CASEY: Why doesn’t it matter?

1349
01:29:06,509 --> 01:29:07,927
And who might you be?

1350
01:29:09,554 --> 01:29:11,054
I’m Casey.

1351
01:29:11,388 --> 01:29:12,639
Newton.

1352
01:29:13,723 --> 01:29:15,642
And who might you be?

1353
01:29:16,560 --> 01:29:17,894
David Nix.

1354
01:29:18,937 --> 01:29:20,272
Pleasure.

1355
01:29:20,647 --> 01:29:22,941
Well, Frank, it’s been
wonderful catching up,

1356
01:29:23,024 --> 01:29:26,278
but as we were fairly clear
about the terms of your exile

1357
01:29:26,361 --> 01:29:28,405
and the consequences of violating it,

1358
01:29:28,488 --> 01:29:29,780
I have to ask...

1359
01:29:29,863 --> 01:29:31,574
what the hell are you doing here?

1360
01:29:31,740 --> 01:29:33,659
I think she can fix it.

1361
01:29:36,620 --> 01:29:37,621
I’m sorry.

1362
01:29:37,955 --> 01:29:39,039
Her.

1363
01:29:39,290 --> 01:29:40,749
I think she can fix it, David.

1364
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:42,084
Wait, what?

1365
01:29:42,209 --> 01:29:43,419
I’ve been pirating your signal.

1366
01:29:43,502 --> 01:29:46,297
Every time you turn it on here,
I can see it there.

1367
01:29:46,380 --> 01:29:48,090
And it flickered.

1368
01:29:48,173 --> 01:29:50,426
The percentage dropped, David.

1369
01:29:51,010 --> 01:29:52,177
Impossible.

1370
01:29:52,595 --> 01:29:54,346
You don’t believe me?
Let’s go find out right now.

1371
01:29:54,555 --> 01:29:56,599
I’m sorry, what can I fix?

1372
01:29:56,890 --> 01:29:58,809
The world, Ms Newton.

1373
01:30:00,019 --> 01:30:02,688
He thinks you can fix the world.

1374
01:30:25,919 --> 01:30:28,464
Is that like a portal to Earth?

1375
01:30:29,048 --> 01:30:31,884
No. It is a bridgeway to Earth.

1376
01:30:37,848 --> 01:30:40,309
Welcome back to the Monitor, Frank.

1377
01:30:41,560 --> 01:30:43,604
It’s something, isn’t it?

1378
01:30:44,271 --> 01:30:45,563
Yeah, it’s something.

1379
01:31:02,246 --> 01:31:04,457
Don’t worry about the light show.

1380
01:31:04,540 --> 01:31:06,584
It’s perfectly safe.

1381
01:31:09,087 --> 01:31:11,964
- Am I supposed to do something?
- Uh-huh.

1382
01:31:12,090 --> 01:31:13,716
Okay, could you be a bit more specific?

1383
01:31:13,800 --> 01:31:15,468
Because fixing
the world sounds a little...

1384
01:31:15,843 --> 01:31:17,470
Just be yourself.

1385
01:31:18,221 --> 01:31:19,555
Gotcha.

1386
01:31:22,642 --> 01:31:24,060
GOVERNOR NIX: Flashes of the future.

1387
01:31:24,310 --> 01:31:25,812
What are those?

1388
01:31:25,895 --> 01:31:27,605
Flashes of future.

1389
01:31:28,272 --> 01:31:30,692
This is us a few seconds from now.

1390
01:31:30,775 --> 01:31:34,696
This whole tower
funnels energy via tachyon,

1391
01:31:34,779 --> 01:31:37,115
a particle that moves
significantly faster than light.

1392
01:31:37,198 --> 01:31:39,867
We discovered them
almost 40 years ago.

1393
01:31:39,951 --> 01:31:43,037
Your physicists are still arguing
over whether they exist.

1394
01:31:43,121 --> 01:31:44,913
GOVERNOR NIX: Oh, dear.

1395
01:31:45,163 --> 01:31:46,206
Too late.

1396
01:31:46,289 --> 01:31:47,833
Oh, dear.

1397
01:31:48,333 --> 01:31:49,417
Too late.

1398
01:32:05,891 --> 01:32:07,643
GOVERNOR NIX: So, on with the show.

1399
01:32:09,061 --> 01:32:11,063
We’ve enhanced
the interface significantly

1400
01:32:11,147 --> 01:32:14,442
but it still functions
on your original algorithm.

1401
01:32:15,693 --> 01:32:18,278
You have something to show me, Frank?

1402
01:32:18,361 --> 01:32:19,821
Show me.

1403
01:32:31,458 --> 01:32:32,958
Pick a place.

1404
01:32:34,001 --> 01:32:36,086
- What?
- A location anywhere in the world.

1405
01:32:36,170 --> 01:32:37,546
Pick one.

1406
01:32:39,381 --> 01:32:40,507
Canaveral.

1407
01:32:41,467 --> 01:32:43,051
Cape Canaveral.

1408
01:32:56,857 --> 01:32:58,357
Easy, easy.

1409
01:32:58,691 --> 01:33:02,862
The interface is oriented from
your hands to the centre of the Earth.

1410
01:33:03,321 --> 01:33:05,364
Yeah, yeah, yeah. I got it.

1411
01:33:10,870 --> 01:33:12,789
You trained her obviously.

1412
01:33:12,872 --> 01:33:15,208
I just met her yesterday.

1413
01:33:15,374 --> 01:33:17,210
She knows how things work.

1414
01:33:21,047 --> 01:33:24,800
<i>You told me this story my entire life
and now I’m telling you.

1415
01:33:24,883 --> 01:33:26,383
CASEY: How is this possible?

1416
01:33:26,467 --> 01:33:29,260
GOVERNOR NIX: We are
millions of exponential deviances

1417
01:33:29,344 --> 01:33:31,721
away from the dimension you call home.

1418
01:33:31,805 --> 01:33:34,224
Frank had the novel idea
of building this machine

1419
01:33:34,307 --> 01:33:36,601
so that we could keep in touch.

1420
01:33:38,101 --> 01:33:39,937
This is three days ago.

1421
01:33:40,020 --> 01:33:41,396
Relatively.

1422
01:33:42,856 --> 01:33:45,192
That’s space/time humour.

1423
01:33:47,903 --> 01:33:51,114
Because tachyons
travel faster than light,

1424
01:33:51,240 --> 01:33:52,616
once we harness them...

1425
01:33:52,699 --> 01:33:54,575
You can see backwards in time.

1426
01:33:55,701 --> 01:33:57,077
Not just backwards.

1427
01:33:59,286 --> 01:34:00,287
You’re kidding.

1428
01:34:01,497 --> 01:34:02,540
No.

1429
01:34:27,356 --> 01:34:28,816
What happened?

1430
01:34:29,149 --> 01:34:30,651
GOVERNOR NIX: Keep going.

1431
01:34:31,151 --> 01:34:33,111
Just a little further.

1432
01:34:49,294 --> 01:34:51,421
[EXPLOSION]

1433
01:34:55,425 --> 01:34:57,301
[INDISTINCT CLAMOURING]

1434
01:35:19,281 --> 01:35:20,532
That’s enough.

1435
01:35:22,784 --> 01:35:24,160
That’s enough, kid.

1436
01:35:28,080 --> 01:35:29,081
[GASPS]

1437
01:35:29,957 --> 01:35:31,249
That’s my house.

1438
01:35:32,459 --> 01:35:36,004
GOVERNOR NIX: It would have been
nice if Frank had prepared you for this...

1439
01:35:36,379 --> 01:35:38,882
but I’m afraid the world is ending.

1440
01:35:39,299 --> 01:35:42,761
It is certain, it is unavoidable...

1441
01:35:42,844 --> 01:35:44,346
and it is coming.

1442
01:35:44,679 --> 01:35:45,805
When?

1443
01:35:47,641 --> 01:35:50,060
This is 58 days from now.

1444
01:35:50,143 --> 01:35:52,437
58 days?

1445
01:35:52,520 --> 01:35:55,523
But whatever caused this could happen
any time after the static starts.

1446
01:35:56,024 --> 01:35:57,734
It could be a month.

1447
01:35:57,817 --> 01:35:59,611
It could be sooner.

1448
01:36:08,411 --> 01:36:11,247
Still looking for your flicker, Frank?

1449
01:36:11,373 --> 01:36:12,540
I know what I saw.

1450
01:36:14,626 --> 01:36:16,878
So why aren’t you telling anyone?

1451
01:36:16,962 --> 01:36:19,255
The whole planet is gonna die

1452
01:36:19,339 --> 01:36:21,466
and you’re just sitting here?

1453
01:36:22,217 --> 01:36:23,551
We’re not gonna die.

1454
01:36:24,260 --> 01:36:26,471
This is your world, not ours.

1455
01:36:26,554 --> 01:36:28,181
We’ll be perfectly fine here.

1456
01:36:28,515 --> 01:36:30,684
Then why don’t you let people in?

1457
01:36:31,685 --> 01:36:32,769
Tell her, David.

1458
01:36:32,852 --> 01:36:34,479
Oh, Frank.

1459
01:36:35,855 --> 01:36:39,150
All those years in exile,
and you still don’t understand.

1460
01:36:39,234 --> 01:36:41,861
These people are driven by savagery.

1461
01:36:42,362 --> 01:36:45,281
If we told them about this place

1462
01:36:45,949 --> 01:36:49,244
then that would happen here to us.

1463
01:36:49,327 --> 01:36:50,578
Then nothing would survive.

1464
01:36:51,079 --> 01:36:53,164
But it hasn’t happened yet!

1465
01:36:53,248 --> 01:36:55,709
Actually, it has happened.
You just haven’t accepted it.

1466
01:36:55,875 --> 01:36:57,251
Well, I don’t accept it!

1467
01:37:04,258 --> 01:37:05,342
Did you see that?

1468
01:37:05,759 --> 01:37:06,927
Did you see that?

1469
01:37:07,011 --> 01:37:08,554
David, I know that you saw that.

1470
01:37:08,637 --> 01:37:11,222
That means that there is a chance.
There’s at least a chance...

1471
01:37:13,474 --> 01:37:15,142
[SCREAMS]

1472
01:37:19,103 --> 01:37:20,979
That went quite well, don’t you think?

1473
01:37:21,062 --> 01:37:22,522
What happened?

1474
01:37:22,605 --> 01:37:24,524
You’re being deported.

1475
01:37:25,108 --> 01:37:26,443
Again.

1476
01:37:26,693 --> 01:37:29,278
Well, that’s Nix for you.

1477
01:37:29,361 --> 01:37:31,655
No new ideas.

1478
01:37:31,739 --> 01:37:35,075
Apparently, your 1I10,000 variable
in the inevitability

1479
01:37:35,159 --> 01:37:37,035
wasn’t convincing enough
to change his mind.

1480
01:37:38,119 --> 01:37:39,327
[SIGHS]

1481
01:37:43,457 --> 01:37:44,833
Be gentle.

1482
01:37:55,802 --> 01:37:57,137
You Okay?

1483
01:37:58,847 --> 01:38:00,891
You know, you’d think
somewhere in the zillions

1484
01:38:00,974 --> 01:38:02,601
of questions that I was asking you,

1485
01:38:02,684 --> 01:38:04,519
you could have said,

1486
01:38:04,603 --> 01:38:06,688
“Oh, Casey, that stuff’s
not really the issue

1487
01:38:06,772 --> 01:38:10,192
“because our future-predicting
machine says we’re all gonna die.”

1488
01:38:10,942 --> 01:38:12,736
We did sort of hint at it.

1489
01:38:12,819 --> 01:38:15,614
This place has nothing to do with hope.

1490
01:38:16,031 --> 01:38:17,531
It’s the opposite of hope.

1491
01:38:17,782 --> 01:38:20,659
- Come on. Don’t say that.
- Why not?

1492
01:38:20,743 --> 01:38:21,869
You said it.

1493
01:38:22,787 --> 01:38:24,163
No wonder you gave up.

1494
01:38:24,663 --> 01:38:26,457
That’s before I knew about you.

1495
01:38:26,832 --> 01:38:28,667
I mean, you really...

1496
01:38:28,918 --> 01:38:30,002
You really are special.

1497
01:38:30,127 --> 01:38:32,003
Why do you people
keep saying that to me?

1498
01:38:34,881 --> 01:38:36,257
I’m not!

1499
01:38:41,012 --> 01:38:43,389
Why’d you even give me this, hmm?

1500
01:38:43,473 --> 01:38:46,434
You showed me a place
that was amazing and incredible

1501
01:38:46,518 --> 01:38:48,686
and it was a lie.

1502
01:38:49,854 --> 01:38:51,773
If you’re gonna zap an idea
into people’s heads,

1503
01:38:51,856 --> 01:38:53,399
you should really make sure
that it’s the truth.

1504
01:38:53,483 --> 01:38:56,486
Because you can’t do that.
You can’t just zap...

1505
01:39:01,991 --> 01:39:04,661
[RADIO FREQUENCIES TUNING]

1506
01:39:06,371 --> 01:39:07,413
What?

1507
01:39:08,373 --> 01:39:10,083
Zap an idea into people’s heads.

1508
01:39:13,795 --> 01:39:15,630
You were pirating the signal.

1509
01:39:15,713 --> 01:39:17,215
- How?
- What?

1510
01:39:17,298 --> 01:39:19,551
At your house.
All your TVs, your doomsday room.

1511
01:39:19,634 --> 01:39:21,678
You were boosting the feed
from that Monitor thing.

1512
01:39:21,761 --> 01:39:23,637
- How did you do that?
- No big deal.

1513
01:39:23,720 --> 01:39:25,012
They’re running so much
power through it now,

1514
01:39:25,096 --> 01:39:27,056
a ham radio could pick it up.

1515
01:39:27,140 --> 01:39:30,059
It’s just a matter of
finding the right frequency...

1516
01:39:31,143 --> 01:39:32,978
You grabbed a signal
from another dimension.

1517
01:39:33,562 --> 01:39:35,062
From a machine here.

1518
01:39:35,146 --> 01:39:37,314
That means it’s transmitting there.

1519
01:39:37,523 --> 01:39:40,192
What if it’s not just predicting the future?

1520
01:39:40,734 --> 01:39:42,069
It’s broadcasting it.

1521
01:39:42,570 --> 01:39:44,070
When I touched this thing

1522
01:39:44,195 --> 01:39:46,698
for a few minutes
it felt like anything was possible.

1523
01:39:46,781 --> 01:39:49,325
So then why can’t the opposite happen?

1524
01:39:49,409 --> 01:39:51,911
What if the Monitor is just a giant pin?

1525
01:39:52,078 --> 01:39:53,788
But instead of making you think positive,

1526
01:39:53,872 --> 01:39:56,040
it makes you think negative and it...

1527
01:39:57,332 --> 01:40:02,212
And it’s convincing the whole world
to feed the wrong wolf.

1528
01:40:03,380 --> 01:40:04,548
We need to turn that thing off.

1529
01:40:04,631 --> 01:40:05,757
[DOOR OPENS]

1530
01:40:10,762 --> 01:40:12,014
It’s time to go home.

1531
01:40:18,604 --> 01:40:20,898
FRANK: David. David.

1532
01:40:21,106 --> 01:40:24,109
- Ah, it’s uninhabited and uncharted.
- Listen to me.

1533
01:40:24,193 --> 01:40:26,820
But it looks like a lovely place
to spend your last days.

1534
01:40:27,029 --> 01:40:29,281
David... The Monitor is
acting as an antenna.

1535
01:40:29,364 --> 01:40:31,324
It isn’t just receiving tachyons.

1536
01:40:31,407 --> 01:40:33,409
It is taking a possible future and...

1537
01:40:33,492 --> 01:40:36,453
And amplifying it, transmitting it,
like a feedback loop.

1538
01:40:36,536 --> 01:40:38,371
It’s a self-fulfilling prophecy

1539
01:40:38,455 --> 01:40:39,663
that’s coming from right there.

1540
01:40:39,788 --> 01:40:41,748
But it’s not just showing people
the end of the world,

1541
01:40:41,831 --> 01:40:44,375
it’s giving them the idea over and over
again until they just accept it!

1542
01:40:44,459 --> 01:40:46,961
It’s a ticking time bomb,
and we’re the ones that lit the fuse.

1543
01:40:47,170 --> 01:40:49,631
We still have 58 days
to try and change things.

1544
01:40:49,964 --> 01:40:52,467
But nothing will work
as long as that thing is still on.

1545
01:40:52,550 --> 01:40:54,093
Young lady, I’m gonna assume

1546
01:40:54,177 --> 01:40:56,596
that your knowledge of tachyonic fusion
is a little sketchy.

1547
01:40:56,679 --> 01:40:59,891
Shutting it down is impossible.

1548
01:40:59,974 --> 01:41:01,642
There is no off.

1549
01:41:02,434 --> 01:41:04,686
CASEY: I’m telling you what it’s doing.

1550
01:41:04,811 --> 01:41:06,897
Why don’t you care?

1551
01:41:07,356 --> 01:41:08,899
Because he’s the one that’s doing it.

1552
01:41:15,489 --> 01:41:16,740
Right?

1553
01:41:20,786 --> 01:41:22,329
Let’s imagine.

1554
01:41:23,621 --> 01:41:26,165
If you glimpsed the future

1555
01:41:26,332 --> 01:41:27,832
and were frightened by what you saw,

1556
01:41:27,916 --> 01:41:31,127
what would you do with that information?
You would go to...

1557
01:41:31,795 --> 01:41:34,422
Who? Politicians? Captains of industry?

1558
01:41:34,589 --> 01:41:37,801
And how would you convince them?
With data? Facts?

1559
01:41:38,677 --> 01:41:39,803
Good luck.

1560
01:41:39,886 --> 01:41:41,513
The only facts they won’t challenge

1561
01:41:41,721 --> 01:41:45,392
are the ones that keep the wheels
greased and the dollars rolling in.

1562
01:41:45,475 --> 01:41:47,102
But what if...

1563
01:41:47,185 --> 01:41:50,105
What if there was a way
of skipping the middleman

1564
01:41:50,188 --> 01:41:53,565
and putting the critical news
directly into everyone’s head?

1565
01:41:55,067 --> 01:41:58,862
The probability of widespread
annihilation kept going up.

1566
01:41:59,238 --> 01:42:02,700
The only way to stop it was to show it.

1567
01:42:02,866 --> 01:42:04,118
To scare people straight.

1568
01:42:04,243 --> 01:42:07,620
Because what reasonable human being
wouldn’t be galvanized

1569
01:42:07,704 --> 01:42:10,707
by the potential destruction of everything
they have ever known or loved?

1570
01:42:12,709 --> 01:42:15,461
To save civilization,

1571
01:42:15,545 --> 01:42:17,337
I would show its collapse.

1572
01:42:18,921 --> 01:42:21,882
But how do you think
this vision was received?

1573
01:42:21,966 --> 01:42:23,884
How do you think people responded

1574
01:42:24,051 --> 01:42:25,845
to the prospect of imminent doom?

1575
01:42:25,928 --> 01:42:29,097
They gobbled it up,
like a chocolate éclair.

1576
01:42:30,056 --> 01:42:32,726
They didn’t fear their demise,
they repackaged it.

1577
01:42:33,727 --> 01:42:37,731
It can be enjoyed as video games,
as TV shows, books, movies.

1578
01:42:37,814 --> 01:42:41,484
The entire world wholeheartedly
embraced the apocalypse

1579
01:42:41,693 --> 01:42:44,070
and sprinted towards it
with gleeful abandon.

1580
01:42:44,446 --> 01:42:48,116
Meanwhile, your Earth
was crumbling all around you.

1581
01:42:48,199 --> 01:42:51,828
You’ve got simultaneous epidemics
of obesity and starvation.

1582
01:42:51,911 --> 01:42:52,995
Explain that one.

1583
01:42:53,954 --> 01:42:57,166
Bees and butterflies start to disappear.

1584
01:42:57,249 --> 01:42:58,833
The glaciers melt.

1585
01:42:58,916 --> 01:43:01,961
Algae blooms all around you.

1586
01:43:02,045 --> 01:43:04,005
The coal mine canaries
are dropping dead,

1587
01:43:04,088 --> 01:43:06,758
and you won’t take the hint!

1588
01:43:07,633 --> 01:43:09,093
In every moment,

1589
01:43:09,260 --> 01:43:11,471
there is the possibility of a better future.

1590
01:43:11,596 --> 01:43:13,348
But you people won’t believe it.

1591
01:43:13,431 --> 01:43:14,515
And because you won’t believe it,

1592
01:43:14,599 --> 01:43:17,602
you won’t do what is necessary
to make it a reality.

1593
01:43:17,727 --> 01:43:19,771
So you dwell on this terrible future,

1594
01:43:19,854 --> 01:43:21,730
and you resign yourselves to it.

1595
01:43:21,813 --> 01:43:22,856
For one reason,

1596
01:43:22,939 --> 01:43:27,194
because that future
doesn’t ask anything of you today.

1597
01:43:29,529 --> 01:43:30,781
So, yes,

1598
01:43:30,906 --> 01:43:33,784
we saw the iceberg,
we warned the Titanic.

1599
01:43:35,284 --> 01:43:38,704
But you all just steered for it anyway,
full steam ahead.

1600
01:43:38,788 --> 01:43:40,122
Why?

1601
01:43:41,206 --> 01:43:43,249
Because you want to sink.

1602
01:43:44,917 --> 01:43:46,377
You gave up.

1603
01:43:48,420 --> 01:43:50,422
That’s not the Monitor’s fault.

1604
01:43:50,506 --> 01:43:51,632
That’s yours.

1605
01:43:55,803 --> 01:43:56,970
Put them through.

1606
01:44:01,183 --> 01:44:03,268
Thanks for visiting, Frank.

1607
01:44:04,144 --> 01:44:06,521
It was genuinely nice to see you again.

1608
01:44:06,604 --> 01:44:07,605
Hmm.

1609
01:44:15,154 --> 01:44:16,155
[BEEPS]

1610
01:44:16,614 --> 01:44:18,366
- What are you doing?
- Not giving up.

1611
01:44:21,369 --> 01:44:22,495
[GRUNTS]

1612
01:44:23,413 --> 01:44:24,414
[YELPS]

1613
01:44:31,087 --> 01:44:32,088
Oh!

1614
01:44:32,880 --> 01:44:33,881
[BRACELET BEEPS]

1615
01:44:35,591 --> 01:44:36,675
Look out!

1616
01:44:40,846 --> 01:44:42,097
[GRUNTS]

1617
01:44:42,305 --> 01:44:44,265
- Get the thing!
- What thing?

1618
01:44:44,348 --> 01:44:47,059
The thing I gave you
when we first got here!

1619
01:44:49,061 --> 01:44:51,188
Arm it! Get on the platform!

1620
01:44:56,485 --> 01:44:57,528
Ah!

1621
01:44:58,195 --> 01:44:59,279
Casey!

1622
01:44:59,362 --> 01:45:00,530
The bomb!

1623
01:45:00,864 --> 01:45:02,699
Get on the platform!

1624
01:45:21,759 --> 01:45:23,343
- Now what?
- Arm it!

1625
01:45:23,427 --> 01:45:24,635
How?

1626
01:45:41,736 --> 01:45:43,654
[WHIMPERING]

1627
01:45:44,238 --> 01:45:45,698
- [BEEPING]
- [GASPS]

1628
01:45:51,746 --> 01:45:52,872
[POWERING DOWN]

1629
01:45:54,080 --> 01:45:55,081
[ROBOT BEEPS]

1630
01:46:09,304 --> 01:46:11,096
[BOTH GRUNTING]

1631
01:46:19,772 --> 01:46:21,232
[BOMB BEEPING]

1632
01:46:29,031 --> 01:46:30,866
[SCREAMS]

1633
01:46:32,493 --> 01:46:33,953
[SCREAMS]

1634
01:46:51,637 --> 01:46:52,888
Casey!

1635
01:46:57,309 --> 01:46:58,852
The bomb!

1636
01:46:58,936 --> 01:47:00,144
Where is the bomb?

1637
01:47:17,328 --> 01:47:18,746
[EXCLAIMS]

1638
01:47:19,872 --> 01:47:20,999
[BOMB BEEPING]

1639
01:47:21,082 --> 01:47:24,043
<i>FEMALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
One minute to detonation.

1640
01:47:27,547 --> 01:47:28,839
<i>- 45 seconds.</i>
- [YELLS]

1641
01:47:28,922 --> 01:47:30,424
Athena! The bomb.

1642
01:47:30,507 --> 01:47:31,967
What do I do? How do I turn it off?

1643
01:47:32,050 --> 01:47:33,342
<i>30 seconds.

1644
01:47:33,426 --> 01:47:34,760
You can’t.

1645
01:47:37,137 --> 01:47:38,345
[LAUGHING]

1646
01:47:38,429 --> 01:47:40,389
This is not funny!

1647
01:47:43,766 --> 01:47:46,394
CASEY: Frank, get out of there!
It’s gonna blow!

1648
01:47:46,477 --> 01:47:48,813
Frank, get out!

1649
01:47:50,607 --> 01:47:51,608
Ah!

1650
01:47:51,691 --> 01:47:52,899
Get out of there!

1651
01:47:52,983 --> 01:47:54,526
<i>FEMALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
Four. Three.

1652
01:47:54,610 --> 01:47:55,652
CASEY: Close the portal!

1653
01:47:55,736 --> 01:47:57,404
<i>- Two. One.</i>
- Close the portal!

1654
01:47:57,529 --> 01:47:59,239
[EXPLOSION]

1655
01:48:06,872 --> 01:48:08,748
[SCREAMING]

1656
01:48:27,266 --> 01:48:28,392
FRANK: Are you all right?

1657
01:48:28,476 --> 01:48:29,684
CASEY: The bomb’s gone.

1658
01:48:29,768 --> 01:48:30,894
- Can you stand?
- Yeah.

1659
01:48:30,977 --> 01:48:32,604
- GOVERNOR NIX: Frank!
- [LASER POWERING UP]

1660
01:48:34,064 --> 01:48:35,065
[GASPS]

1661
01:48:36,399 --> 01:48:37,400
No.

1662
01:48:39,235 --> 01:48:41,029
CASEY: The bomb’s gone.

1663
01:48:41,112 --> 01:48:42,822
FRANK: Can you stand?
CASEY: Yeah.

1664
01:48:42,947 --> 01:48:44,323
- Frank!
- [LASER POWERING UP]

1665
01:48:44,406 --> 01:48:45,407
[SCREAMS]

1666
01:48:58,587 --> 01:48:59,588
What happened? Is she okay?

1667
01:48:59,672 --> 01:49:01,006
I need to get her to a repair module.

1668
01:49:01,090 --> 01:49:02,257
Frank!

1669
01:49:02,758 --> 01:49:04,967
No one’s going to repair me.

1670
01:49:05,051 --> 01:49:06,761
Not in time.

1671
01:49:07,053 --> 01:49:09,138
I need to tell you something now.

1672
01:49:16,645 --> 01:49:18,605
Oh, darn.

1673
01:49:18,939 --> 01:49:20,523
I’m shutting down.

1674
01:49:20,606 --> 01:49:23,025
<i>[DISTORTED] I’m shutting down.

1675
01:49:25,319 --> 01:49:26,946
I’m going to lose sync.

1676
01:49:28,280 --> 01:49:29,948
Don’t look at me like that.

1677
01:49:30,115 --> 01:49:33,868
If I lose sync it’s not failure.

1678
01:49:34,119 --> 01:49:35,327
I know.

1679
01:49:37,329 --> 01:49:40,749
There are things I need to tell you
before the final...

1680
01:49:41,417 --> 01:49:44,002
Before the automated program kicks in.

1681
01:49:44,920 --> 01:49:46,463
I’m a machine.

1682
01:49:47,089 --> 01:49:49,383
I never thought that was bad

1683
01:49:49,466 --> 01:49:51,677
until I saw your face
when you found out I was.

1684
01:49:51,760 --> 01:49:52,970
I always knew.

1685
01:49:54,470 --> 01:49:56,054
No, you didn’t.

1686
01:49:56,221 --> 01:49:57,556
<i>FEMALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
Systems failing.

1687
01:49:57,639 --> 01:50:01,560
<i>Activating last thoughts
saved for Frank Walker.

1688
01:50:02,394 --> 01:50:04,938
<i>ATHENA: Log 15: September...

1689
01:50:05,564 --> 01:50:07,190
<i>1965.

1690
01:50:07,899 --> 01:50:11,945
<i>Frank Walker is looking at me
in a manner that is difficult to recognize.

1691
01:50:12,904 --> 01:50:14,656
<i>It seems imperative to explain to him

1692
01:50:14,740 --> 01:50:16,074
<i>that I am an Audio-Animatronic...

1693
01:50:16,158 --> 01:50:17,284
Athena...

1694
01:50:17,451 --> 01:50:21,288
<i>But I am concerned
that he may be adversely affected

1695
01:50:21,496 --> 01:50:23,707
<i>when he finds out that I am not human.

1696
01:50:24,875 --> 01:50:26,459
<i>He has potential.

1697
01:50:26,625 --> 01:50:28,209
<i>I don’t want to damage it.

1698
01:50:28,835 --> 01:50:31,296
<i>He needs someone to believe in him.

1699
01:50:31,463 --> 01:50:33,590
<i>And I am fulfilling that need.

1700
01:50:34,257 --> 01:50:35,675
<i>He is my top recruit.

1701
01:50:37,927 --> 01:50:41,806
<i>Log 24, October, 1965.

1702
01:50:43,682 --> 01:50:46,518
<i>I’m having unusual thoughts
towards Frank Walker.

1703
01:50:46,977 --> 01:50:50,022
<i>I suspect a flaw
in my empathy interface.

1704
01:50:50,189 --> 01:50:52,524
<i>I am thinking I should report it.

1705
01:50:54,234 --> 01:50:56,153
<i>But I haven’t.

1706
01:50:56,320 --> 01:50:58,280
<i>I cannot explain why.

1707
01:50:59,364 --> 01:51:01,909
<i>Log 78, April...

1708
01:51:02,367 --> 01:51:03,869
<i>1984.

1709
01:51:04,161 --> 01:51:07,289
<i>Frank Walker has been banished
by Governor Nix.

1710
01:51:07,456 --> 01:51:09,166
<i>He says he has lost hope

1711
01:51:09,249 --> 01:51:12,961
<i>and he holds me responsible for
having given it to him in the first place.

1712
01:51:13,504 --> 01:51:15,881
<i>I do not understand this.

1713
01:51:16,048 --> 01:51:17,966
<i>He says I never will

1714
01:51:18,050 --> 01:51:22,011
<i>because I do not feel
anger or disappointment.

1715
01:51:24,806 --> 01:51:26,432
<i>Or love.

1716
01:51:28,434 --> 01:51:30,478
<i>FEMALE AUTOMATED VOICE:
End recording.

1717
01:51:33,356 --> 01:51:35,900
I was designed to find dreamers.

1718
01:51:36,359 --> 01:51:37,735
I found you.

1719
01:51:41,280 --> 01:51:42,740
And lost you.

1720
01:51:44,700 --> 01:51:45,992
Till I found her.

1721
01:51:47,576 --> 01:51:48,744
Casey.

1722
01:51:51,747 --> 01:51:54,875
Dreamers need to stick together.

1723
01:51:58,087 --> 01:51:59,922
It’s not programming.

1724
01:52:00,714 --> 01:52:02,216
It’s personal.

1725
01:52:05,511 --> 01:52:07,346
[SYSTEM BEEPING]

1726
01:52:09,682 --> 01:52:10,974
The Monitor.

1727
01:52:11,057 --> 01:52:14,686
The bomb is gone. But I’m not, yet.

1728
01:52:15,103 --> 01:52:16,813
There isn’t much time.

1729
01:52:16,896 --> 01:52:19,107
My self-destruct, use it.

1730
01:52:20,024 --> 01:52:22,443
You know what to do, Frank.

1731
01:52:23,111 --> 01:52:25,696
Help get it right this time.

1732
01:52:26,363 --> 01:52:27,781
[SIGHS]

1733
01:52:29,032 --> 01:52:30,784
I thought you can’t have ideas.

1734
01:52:31,535 --> 01:52:34,120
Well, what do you know?

1735
01:52:37,123 --> 01:52:38,623
What do you know.

1736
01:52:40,041 --> 01:52:41,293
[BEEPING SPEEDS UP]

1737
01:52:41,751 --> 01:52:43,419
Systems failing.

1738
01:53:25,377 --> 01:53:27,253
- Frank?
- Yeah?

1739
01:53:28,713 --> 01:53:32,008
Do you want to know
why you could never make me laugh?

1740
01:53:33,927 --> 01:53:35,135
Why?

1741
01:53:36,803 --> 01:53:38,847
Because you’re not funny.

1742
01:53:42,768 --> 01:53:44,895
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1743
01:53:50,901 --> 01:53:53,195
You can let me go now.

1744
01:53:59,993 --> 01:54:01,620
Goodbye, Frank.

1745
01:54:05,123 --> 01:54:07,167
[BEEPING RAPIDLY]

1746
01:54:10,212 --> 01:54:11,880
Goodbye, Athena.

1747
01:54:23,684 --> 01:54:25,227
[EXPLOSION]

1748
01:54:41,952 --> 01:54:43,244
Oh, bollocks.

1749
01:54:48,082 --> 01:54:49,582
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

1750
01:54:49,666 --> 01:54:50,958
[GRUNTS]

1751
01:55:05,431 --> 01:55:07,015
[GRUNTING]

1752
01:55:23,614 --> 01:55:24,949
[PANTING]

1753
01:55:34,292 --> 01:55:35,584
FRANK: Now what?

1754
01:55:37,669 --> 01:55:39,296
You’re asking me?

1755
01:55:39,921 --> 01:55:41,673
This was your idea, kid.

1756
01:55:43,884 --> 01:55:44,968
Yeah.

1757
01:55:47,971 --> 01:55:49,514
You think it Will work?

1758
01:55:51,767 --> 01:55:54,061
I guess we have to make it work.

1759
01:55:57,314 --> 01:55:58,565
[SIGHS]

1760
01:56:09,576 --> 01:56:11,870
<i>FRANK: So, we’re making it work.

1761
01:56:12,496 --> 01:56:14,206
<i>CASEY: First order of business,

1762
01:56:15,207 --> 01:56:16,666
<i>get the door back open.

1763
01:56:21,797 --> 01:56:25,675
<i>Couldn’t hurt to get a few
experienced engineers over here.

1764
01:56:29,805 --> 01:56:30,889
Next. . .

1765
01:56:31,223 --> 01:56:33,600
<i>FRANK: Put the party back on.

1766
01:56:35,852 --> 01:56:38,396
<i>And print out some new invitations.

1767
01:56:40,607 --> 01:56:43,360
<i>Which brings us to
why we’re here today.

1768
01:56:44,152 --> 01:56:47,030
A year ago,
it was all supposed to be over.

1769
01:56:47,114 --> 01:56:49,199
We shouldn’t even be here.

1770
01:56:49,282 --> 01:56:50,658
But we are.

1771
01:56:52,034 --> 01:56:55,538
It isn’t hard to knock down
a big, evil building

1772
01:56:55,621 --> 01:56:58,916
that’s telling everybody
that the world’s gonna end.

1773
01:56:59,500 --> 01:57:01,043
What is hard

1774
01:57:02,335 --> 01:57:04,920
is figuring out what to build in its place.

1775
01:57:06,004 --> 01:57:08,257
And if we’re gonna do that,

1776
01:57:08,340 --> 01:57:10,092
we can’t do it alone.

1777
01:57:10,843 --> 01:57:13,052
We’re gonna need all of you.

1778
01:57:14,512 --> 01:57:18,057
- Frank Walker, may I ask a question?
- Sure.

1779
01:57:18,141 --> 01:57:20,350
The search parameters you’ve given us,

1780
01:57:20,433 --> 01:57:23,145
while mathematically sound, are a bit...

1781
01:57:24,187 --> 01:57:25,689
undeﬁned.

1782
01:57:26,398 --> 01:57:28,817
Could you be more specific, please?

1783
01:57:28,984 --> 01:57:30,527
Well, Miss Newton,

1784
01:57:31,444 --> 01:57:34,531
you wanna tell our new recruiters
what they’re looking for?

1785
01:57:34,614 --> 01:57:35,990
Dreamers.

1786
01:57:36,532 --> 01:57:39,785
We are looking for dreamers.

1787
01:57:41,871 --> 01:57:43,747
Anyone who will feed the right wolf.

1788
01:57:54,592 --> 01:57:58,262
So, I once told your predecessor

1789
01:57:58,888 --> 01:58:02,683
that she was nothing
but a combination of ones and zeroes.

1790
01:58:06,478 --> 01:58:08,105
I was wrong.

1791
01:58:08,272 --> 01:58:09,899
She was much more than that.

1792
01:58:10,608 --> 01:58:13,235
You are much more than that, too.

1793
01:58:13,444 --> 01:58:16,530
So, go out there
and do what she would have done.

1794
01:58:17,781 --> 01:58:19,825
Find the ones who haven’t given up.

1795
01:58:20,909 --> 01:58:22,701
They’re the future.

1796
01:58:27,664 --> 01:58:28,790
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

1797
01:58:28,957 --> 01:58:31,460
[ALL APPLAUDING]

1798
01:58:56,068 --> 01:58:58,528
[PLAYING BLUES RIFF]
